│                                                                                            │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue ###                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `instcombine` pass is crashing with an assertion failure `isa<Instruction>(Val)`       │
│ inside `llvm::cast`. This happens when trying to simplify an `add` instruction whose       │
│ operands are `shl` instructions. The `shl` instructions, in turn, operate on a `ptrtoint`  │
│ constant expression. The crash indicates that the code is attempting to cast a `Value*` to │
│ an `Instruction*`, but the `Value` is not an `Instruction`.                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log ###                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `opt` log and backtrace show that the crash occurs within the `visitAdd` function,     │
│ which calls `foldUsingDistributiveLaws`, leading to `tryFactorization`. The instruction    │
│ being processed is `%add = add i32 %shl, %shl`. The operands `%shl` are `shl i32 ptrtoint  │
│ (ptr @g to i32), 1`. The `ptrtoint` is a `ConstantExpr`, which is a `Constant`, not an     │
│ `Instruction`.                                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis ###                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is an incorrect assumption in the `tryFactorization` function. This         │
│ function is part of the logic that handles distributive laws, like `(A*B) + (A*C) ->       │
│ A*(B+C)`. In our case, the `add` is `shl+shl`, which is `shl*2`. The `shl` is `(ptrtoint   │
│ << 1)`. The factorization logic tries to analyze the components of the (potential)         │
│ multiplications.                                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The function `tryFactorization` receives `Op00`, `Op01`, `Op10`, and `Op11` as `Value*`.   │
│ It then attempts to match patterns. In one of the paths, it assumes that if `Op00` and     │
│ `Op10` are the same, one of them can be safely cast to an `Instruction`. However, in our   │
│ reproducer, `Op00` (and `Op10`) is the `ptrtoint` constant expression. `ConstantExpr` is a │
│ subclass of `Constant` and `Value`, but not `Instruction`. The `cast<Instruction>` on this │
│ `ConstantExpr` thus fails the `isa<Instruction>` check and aborts.                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that the `Value` is an `Instruction` before attempting the cast.      │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s) ###                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The edit is in `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp`, inside the      │
│ `tryFactorization` function. We need to add a check to ensure `Op00` is an instruction     │
│ before casting it.                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ // Op00*Op01 + Op10*Op11 -> (Op01+Op11)*Op00                                               │
│ if (Op00 == Op10) {                                                                        │
│   // Bail if the expression is not of the form (X*C) + (X*C)                               │
│   if (!isa<Constant>(Op01) || !isa<Constant>(Op11))                                        │
│     return nullptr;                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│   // TODO: Check for no-wrap.                                                              │
│   Value *V = Builder.CreateAdd(Op01, Op11);                                                │
│   // If the shared operand is a PHI, it's likely that we are un-doing                      │
│   // a distribution that was required to create fowarding opportunities.                   │
│   // Only fold if the result of the add is a constant.                                     │
│   if (isa<PHINode>(Op00) && !isa<Constant>(V))                                             │
│     return nullptr;                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│   // Do not create a multiply if the shared operand is an add.                             │
│   // It is almost always better to keep the expression in sum-of-products form.            │
│   if (isa<Instruction>(Op00) &&                                                            │
│       cast<Instruction>(Op00)->getOpcode() == Instruction::Add)                            │
│     return nullptr;                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│   return Builder.CreateMul(V, Op00);                                                       │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problematic line is `cast<Instruction>(Op00)->getOpcode()`. I will add a check before  │
│ it.                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion ###                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The proposed fix adds a guard to `tryFactorization` to ensure that a `Value*` is an        │
│ `Instruction*` before casting and dereferencing it. This prevents the crash when           │
│ `instcombine` encounters a pattern involving constant expressions that are not             │
│ instructions. This makes the factorization logic more robust and correctly handles the     │
│ provided reproducer without crashing.                                                      │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
